Indie-Rock (66) – Fits best for 2000s-style emo (Dashboard Confessional, Jimmy Eat World, The Get Up Kids, etc.). Very similar instrumentation, structure, and emotional tone.
Punk (25) – Emo grew out of punk and hardcore. The 1980s emocore era (Rites of Spring, Embrace) is a direct offshoot of punk.
Hardcore (109) – Emo started as “emocore” (emotional hardcore). First-wave emo is essentially a variant of hardcore.
Post-Punk (89) – Shares mood and structural ideas with early emo and post-hardcore.
Post-Rock (26) – Some emo bands use similar dynamics and atmospherics (explosive builds, long instrumental sections).
Power-Pop (111) – Relevant for the poppier, hook-oriented side of emo-pop.